generated_description:  Theo van Rysselberghe's "The Valley of the Sambre" (1890) exemplifies Post-Impressionism's focus on color theory and optical effects. Using pointillism, Rysselberghe captures the serene Belgian landscape, reflecting the era's fascination with scientific advancements in optics. This naturalistic yet innovative approach highlights the interplay of light and color, emphasizing the harmony of rural life during the late 19th century. The painting celebrates the beauty of untouched nature, resonating with the period's growing environmental awareness.

